quote: The Jamaican dollar replaced the Jamaican pound on September 8, 1969 at a rate of J$2 = J£1.

"The next move to introduce British sterling silver coinage to the colonies came with an imperial order-in-council dated 1825. ... In 1949, the British government formalized the dollar system of accounts in British Guiana and the Eastern Caribbean territories by introducing the British West Indies dollar (BWI$) at the already existing conversion rate of $4.80 per pound sterling (or $1 = 4 shillings 2 pence)."
